{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9b0ef030-9379-462b-ac4a-1ce19495aead","content":"The working directory is empty (no repo to search), so I'll answer based on .NET MAUI knowledge:\n\n**`ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`** — ✅ This is correct for .NET MAUI on .NET 10. You need the platform-specific namespace:\n\n```xml\nxmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n```\n\nThis pads your page content to respect the safe area (notch/Dynamic Island).\n\n**`IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on a Grid** — ❌ This is **not** a real .NET MAUI property. There's no built-in `IgnoreSafeArea` on layouts. Your tutorial may be outdated or incorrect.\n\n### For a full-bleed background image with safe content:\n\nInstead, structure your layout so the image fills the whole page while content respects the safe area:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"...\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n    <Grid>\n        <!-- Background stretches edge-to-edge -->\n        <Image Source=\"bg.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n        \n        <!-- Content respects safe area via padding -->\n        <Grid Padding=\"{OnPlatform iOS='20,60,20,34'}\">\n            <!-- Your content here -->\n        </Grid>\n    </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nOr better, set `UseSafeArea=\"True\"` on the page and use a negative margin on the background image, or place the image in a handler/custom renderer that ignores safe area insets.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6ad0d16d-d8e1-4ce8-b5f9-7631a717596b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The working directory is empty - there's no repository to search. The user is asking a general question about .NET MAUI safe area APIs for .NET 10. Let me answer based on my knowledge.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the safe area handling has evolved:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` - This is the **Xamarin.Forms** approach using the iOS platform-specific. In .NET MAUI, this was carried forward but the namespace changed. In .NET MAUI, you'd use `xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"` and then `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`.\n\n\n2. There's no built-in `IgnoreSafeArea` property on standard layouts in .NET MAUI - that might be a Xamarin.Forms concept or a custom implementation. For .NET 10, I should check what improvements Microsoft has made to safe area handling, though the core approach likely remains the same with platform-specific APIs.\n\nActually, thinking through this more carefully: the `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` approach is the standard way to handle safe areas in .NET MAUI, requiring the iOS platform-specific namespace. The `IgnoreSafeArea` property the user mentioned doesn't exist as a standard MAUI property, so their tutorial might be using outdated Xamarin.Forms terminology or a custom solution.\n\nFor the specific use case of extending a background image to the edges while keeping content inset, I'd disable `UseSafeArea` on the page itself and then manually apply padding to the inner content that needs to respect the safe area boundaries.\n\nThere's no `IgnoreSafeArea` property in standard .NET MAUI, so that tutorial might be referencing a custom solution or outdated information—I should clarify what actually works.","outputTokens":1191,"requestId":"080F:1C0BED:54E62:62365:69F2AB5D"},"id":"753045a8-b3be-4314-acc9-fc4f317fd6f9","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:08:04.029Z","parentId":"288b8977-134b-4f97-a443-4aab03ab41fb"}
